<subsection xml:id="subsec-linear-motion-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Linear Motion in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_9zw66ngb">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_6fens9ch">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_uzsbjz1g">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gkatv2rx">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hxtfykln">
                        2.10 Linear Motion
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_s6jfcx2l">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cjd9f8ck">
                        Apply linear motion principles to solve real-life problems in transportation safety, sports, and engineering.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iphxbt8v" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_pd28x1f4">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_p8urqp8k" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fgtxi9wh">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_i1hw5539" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_t1z24qdu"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0b2cn84i">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fvcc3trd">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Linear motion principles underpin transportation safety (stopping distances), sports performance (acceleration analysis), and engineering design (elevator motion). Stopping distance comprises reaction distance plus braking distance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_37zaqoyc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fl3ugyqu">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate reaction distance, braking distance, and total stopping distance. Apply equations of motion (<m>v = u + at</m>, <m>s = ut + \frac{1}{2}at^2</m>, <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>) to real-life scenarios.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jf4153f8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_1ndwbu3h">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Analyse real-world safety situations, make recommendations about speed limits and road design, and evaluate whether vehicles can stop safely in given conditions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_a39r9ktj">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/linear-motion-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kvu013p1">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_linear-motion-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_135fu28e">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_zudzkkqj">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ktcihtjl">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_6vc4is9z">
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_nbywfkry">
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_enh1d7qx">
                    Calculators, chart paper, markers
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_oag4d5ez">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_cz9g983x">
                    Emphasise the real-world context: this is how engineers and planners make safety decisions. Guide students to break the problem into parts: reaction distance, braking distance, total stopping distance.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p xml:id="auto_q7ra1zfb">
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cte5wd5p">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_71352l61">Organise students into groups of 3<ndash/>4.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ctkr0q2f">Encourage discussion about safety margins and recommendations.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_cnjnmu6c">Ask probing questions: <q>What happens if the bus is going faster?</q> <q>Why is reaction time important?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1j2wv1u3">Help students connect calculations to safety implications.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_i5soyiqc">Use student findings as a bridge to formal concepts about motion in real life.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    
        <activity xml:id="auto_pacdqc6w">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_f3u6ada6">
            <p xml:id="auto_vcx8fjw2">
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zasdipul">
                The local government plans to introduce a new school bus stop along a straight road near your school. 
                Before approval, the transport committee needs to determine whether the stopping distance is safe for learners crossing the road.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fkwrvw9f">
                You are part of a team of student consultants tasked with analysing the motion of a school bus using principles of linear motion.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_30zj87zb">
                Your team is given the following data:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8ib8dlcf">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_rmh2cfxu">
                        <p xml:id="auto_k4lyjcuh">
                            The bus is travelling at <m>20</m> m/s along a straight road.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ueesn5ue">
                        <p xml:id="auto_syh5hqfw">
                            The driver notices learners crossing <m>50</m> metres ahead.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_g5cx26n2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_y0c7ihp8">
                            The driver's reaction time is <m>2</m> seconds.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_8lltp7r4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fo6o8o6g">
                            After reacting, the bus decelerates uniformly at <m>4</m> m/s<m>^2</m> until it stops.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_stxe88o1">
                <alert>What to do </alert>
            </p>
            </introduction>

            <task xml:id="auto_15zk8ji2">
                <statement>
                   <p xml:id="auto_kh9k9yyt">
                      Reaction distance is the distance the vehicle travels from the moment the driver perceives a hazard to the moment they apply the brakes.
                   </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_z3vemnht">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_88mjtrdw">
                                <p xml:id="auto_smorfsxo">
                                    Calculate the distance travelled during the <m>2</m>-second reaction time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_uvffne6w">
                                <p xml:id="auto_m250t5i5">
                                    State whether the bus is accelerating, decelerating, or moving at constant velocity during this time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_xwbjfy9s">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_mitt4gve">
                        Braking distance is the distance it takes for the bus to come to a complete stop after the driver starts braking.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_lto5ex4p">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_tkio1arr">
                                <p xml:id="auto_lfkjv31y">
                                    Calculate the time taken for the bus to come to rest after braking begins.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_gi8ah6jn">
                                <p xml:id="auto_e2ht3unt">
                                    Calculate the braking distance using the formula <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_0bdi0a60">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_b41jqo39">
                        Total stopping distance is the sum of the reaction distance and the braking distance.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_piyvgmji">
                        <ol>
                            <li xml:id="auto_3uy1vx2o">
                                <p xml:id="auto_1ayiprrp">
                                    Calculate the total stopping distance of the bus.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_nneptal2">
                                <p xml:id="auto_lxpgwev2">
                                    Compare this with the <m>50</m> m available before the crossing.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_dseogc7a">
                                <p xml:id="auto_yzq3dc09">
                                     Conclude whether the bus will stop in time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_porbtzx0">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8x045ybt">
                        Find:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ank46ddv">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_jm6nhy7d">
                                <p xml:id="auto_hftf58f7">
                                    The total displacement of the bus from the moment the driver notices the learners to when the bus stops.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_fuuysip3">
                                The average velocity during the entire stopping process.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_bbbgdmyi">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fewddqk4">
                        Based on your calculations, recommend one of the following:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hstxfjwa">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_8j6a9ifr">
                                <p xml:id="auto_vq7ld0ko">
                                    Reduce the speed limit
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_yvvrdi7l">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ih8icxss">
                                     Move the bus stop further away
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_vm2nhrkr">
                                <p xml:id="auto_vqztw558">
                                    Install a speed bump
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_8faw3vj2">
                                <p xml:id="auto_av8jf4tj">
                                        Maintain the current arrangement
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_w651ttvj">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_qhlw0nnx">
                      Share your work with other learners
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_g1lg4qx8">
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4lmlouhj">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ygo078ub">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_jyhfo7c6">Address common misconceptions from the anchor activity: clarify that reaction distance occurs at constant velocity (no braking yet) and braking distance involves deceleration.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ibmhovv8">Show why doubling speed more than doubles stopping distance — this surprises many students.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lmth78o9">Use real-world examples to make concepts concrete: school zones, highways, pedestrian crossings.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2out48j4">Connect to prior knowledge of velocity, acceleration, and equations of motion from earlier lessons.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_f8rsrtmk">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0cz1fupv">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_ddpk26xc">Break stopping distance into clearly labelled components: reaction distance + braking distance = total stopping distance.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_piaadh1e">Emphasise that <m>\text{Reaction distance} = \text{speed} \times \text{reaction time}</m> (constant velocity during reaction).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ytwrw8qv">For braking, use <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m> to find braking distance.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_kqexk8az">
        <p xml:id="auto_dpdln6zt">
            Linear motion principles are fundamental in transportation safety.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m6tzcmm5">
             Understanding stopping distances helps engineers and planners design safer roads and establish appropriate speed limits in different zones. 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hk2fjhed">
             The relationship between speed, reaction time, and braking distance directly impacts pedestrian safety and accident prevention.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_llxv4zcf">
           Engineers apply motion calculations when designing vehicles, elevators, and transport systems to ensure safety and efficiency.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ki6uz1e6">
            In sports, motion analysis improves performance by evaluating speed, acceleration, and timing.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6nk70ry4">
            Industries use constant motion principles to control machines and production systems.
        </p>
    </insight>

    
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_s1wesgae">
            Guide students through the worked examples below, then assign independent practice.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_u67y1mb7">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qpzvqhif">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_4qhptsz0">Each example covers a different real-life application: transportation safety, sports performance, and engineering.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_fyh36piy">For Example 1 (car braking), emphasise the connection between deceleration and stopping distance.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sjh0pv8x">For Example 2 (sprinter), highlight how acceleration relates to athletic performance.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2i83e3e5">For Example 3 (elevator), discuss why gradual acceleration matters for passenger comfort.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iik21z2c">After guided examples, assign the individual practice problems for students to work independently.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_ewqc5bye">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_3izz9uut">
                 A car is travelling at a velocity of <m>20</m> m/s. The driver applies brakes and the car comes to rest in <m>5</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zmgc80tg">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_m50rueuh">
                        <p xml:id="auto_yybvx8tc">
                            Calculate the acceleration of the car.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ns8jd4v2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_jaqkb6yz">
                            Calculate the stopping distance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_732t5auv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fpm9gg3s">
                            Explain why higher speeds increase accident risk.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_4rm4u3fy">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_matppxe6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bb4xa8d4">
                             u = <m>20</m> m/s<m>^1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3ect7iyh">
                            v = <m>0</m>m/s <m>^1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mcjr91ip">
                            t = <m>5</m> s
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_kjt6rp5n">
                            a = <m>\frac{-20}{5}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_kywea8kk">
                            a = <m>-4</m> m/s<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_pykylbvk">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ruyuwein">
                            s = ut + <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>at<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_nv0kmr1z">
                           s = <m>50</m> m
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bdb3vwc6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_z02r34df">
                            When the initial speed increases, the stopping distance increases. 
                            A higher velocity means the vehicle covers more distance before it can come to rest, increasing the likelihood of a collision.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
   <example xml:id="auto_46z67xxs">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_fsr7jvkn">
                A sprinter starts from rest and accelerates uniformly at <m>3</m> m/s<m>^2</m> for <m>4</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8euax3v0">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_cb6ggk33">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ddc7l4mm">
                            Calculate the final velocity.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bk5o2a8i">
                        <p xml:id="auto_rhua9ypk">
                            Calculate the distance covered during this time.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_n8anotgy">
                        <p xml:id="auto_220ddd66">
                            Explain how improving acceleration benefits performance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_mcn4ipat">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_3zxlfxek">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bpto5660">
                            v = u + at
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_eaen1nu6">
                            v <m>= 0 + 3 \times 4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0ghxk2hk">
                            <m>= 12 </m>m/s
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ag2d20u0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_dwvm6qwi">
                            Greater acceleration allows an athlete to reach a higher speed in a shorter time. 
                            This provides a competitive advantage, especially at the start of a race.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_4v4z3gej">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_h63ru4wv">
                An elevator accelerates uniformly from rest to <m>4</m> m/s in <m>2</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vo3nppa1">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_23to8q7y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_c0ide79h">
                            Calculate the acceleration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_qnwjk04a">
                        <p xml:id="auto_puyx0irq">
                            Explain why gradual acceleration is important.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_v4ecy434">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_nb1k67ap">
                        <p xml:id="auto_py20vnsc">
                            a = (v - u) / t
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_35pk2fsm">
                            a <m>= \frac{(4 - 0)} {2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_2ebvniic">
                            a<m> = 2</m> m/s<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_cco2y70s">
                        <p xml:id="auto_jv3f1rs9">
                            Gradual acceleration ensures passenger comfort and safety. 
                            Sudden acceleration would cause passengers to lose balance and could result in injury.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- STACK EXERCISES -->
     
    <exercise xml:id="ex-application-of-linear-motion-in-emergency-braking">
        <!--<title></title>-->
        <stack label="stk-application-of-linear-motion-in-emergency-braking" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-9-Linear-Motion/Linear-motion-in-real-life/Application-of-linear-motion-in-emergency-braking.xml"/>
    </exercise>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
               <li xml:id="auto_2vepox6k">
                <p xml:id="auto_8k2ijz04">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
               </li> 
                 <li xml:id="auto_crb4164j">
                    <li xml:id="auto_tmlx2ya0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_h3ki5d4w">
                            <alert>Teacher's Role</alert>
                
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <p xml:id="auto_80j982a9">
                        Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge Learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                    </p>
                 </li>   
                
                
                
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_0lgbbe91">
            Students complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tz2vopz0">
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> A cyclist travelling at <m>5</m> m/s takes <m>2</m> s to react and brake to a stop. A child runs into the road <m>12</m> m ahead. (a) State the equation relating distance, speed and time. (b) Calculate the cyclist's reaction distance. (c) Determine and explain whether the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s499vsih">
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> A delivery truck travels at <m>15</m> m/s. The driver has a reaction time of <m>1.5</m> seconds and can brake with deceleration of <m>5</m> m/s<m>^2</m>. (a) Calculate the reaction distance. (b) Calculate the braking distance. (c) Calculate the total stopping distance. (d) Recommend a safe following distance and justify your answer.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jp3tx4q5">
            <alert>Answer Key (teacher reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6hnjx9zt">
            <alert>Q1:</alert> (a) Distance = speed <m>\times</m> time. (b) Reaction distance = <m>5 \times 2 = 10</m> m. (c) Yes, the cyclist will stop — reaction distance of <m>10</m> m is less than the <m>12</m> m available, leaving a <m>2</m> m safety margin.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_i8iipyh2">
            <alert>Q2:</alert> (a) Reaction distance = <m>15 \times 1.5 = 22.5</m> m. (b) Using <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>: <m>0 = 225 + 2(-5)s</m>, so <m>s = 22.5</m> m. (c) Total = <m>22.5 + 22.5 = 45</m> m. (d) Safe following distance should be at least <m>50</m><ndash/><m>60</m> m to allow a safety margin beyond the stopping distance.
        </p> -->
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="ex-linearmotion-in-real-life">
        
        <exercise xml:id="auto_ichh5ddb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hnv6c95t">
                    A student walks a distance of <m>10</m> m in <m>8 </m> s. 
                    Another student runs the same distance in <m>3</m> s. 
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_gbbaa7pu">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_e572zuuu">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1w2bhrth">
                                Calculate the walking speed.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7u9cawmj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_7c09ie8g">
                                Calculate the running speed.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c3cf0jro">
                            <p xml:id="auto_wqrcgg9h">
                                State how a Physical Education teacher could use this information to plan training.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_rfrpjy3r">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_9kc9a7x0">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1hi540mo">
                                <m>1.25</m> m/s
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_bk9aoxph">
                            <p xml:id="auto_0aep02nl">
                                <m>3.33</m> m/s
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_wx0ex1qs">
                            <p xml:id="auto_d2g6ityg">
                                The teacher can set realistic speed targets and design drills to improve students' acceleration and endurance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_x163s43r">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dabhy1to">
                    A car travels at a constant velocity of <m>20</m> m/s. 
                    The driver has a reaction time of <m>1</m> s.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_rtj5i0wk">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_pea9itjp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_xbz69ssf">
                                Calculate the distance travelled during the driver's reaction time. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_9kqz0nfd">
                            <p xml:id="auto_wz08rjzj">
                               Explain why lower speed limits are enforced in pedestrian areas. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_4zj0wnnx">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_fclszdnq">
                            <p xml:id="auto_80rolmz4">
                                Reaction distance = <m>20 \times 1 = 20</m> m
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_per7fnxe">
                            <p xml:id="auto_61tnt43d">
                                Lower speeds reduce both reaction distance and braking distance, giving drivers more time to stop and improving pedestrian safety. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_d3j3xx4j">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_efw0c6wp">
                    Two cars are travelling at <m>25</m> m/s.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jowlh6ce">
                    Car A comes to rest in <m>5</m> s.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_26be8dmi">
                    Car B comes to rest in <m>8</m> s.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_f8lu0bpe">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_2wbpnkgx">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pjwho61q">
                                Calculate the acceleration of each car.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_bm9qzp3a">
                            <p xml:id="auto_taayokdr">
                                Determine which car has the shorter stopping distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_kewwew6e">
                            <p xml:id="auto_u8d5oqpu">
                                Explain which braking system is more effective.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_pfyr73hf">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_4ngf8wg7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ztdan606">
                               Car A <m>-5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_e1b64359">
                                Car B <m>-3.125 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5dq9xcu2">
                            <p xml:id="auto_0e3xfevx">
                                Car A has the shorter stopping distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rz9if0nn">
                            <p xml:id="auto_c6dns5cu">
                                Car A's braking system is more effective because it produces a larger deceleration. 
                                A greater negative acceleration reduces stopping distance, which improves road safety.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_8pdhy3bd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_9l2a7oto">
                    A cyclist travelling at <m>5</m> m/s takes <m>2</m> s to react and brake to a stop. 
                    A child runs into the road <m>12</m> m ahead.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_kp90gxkl">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_rmms2zb7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_4bdlne6e">
                                State the equation relating distance, speed and time.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_xr9xekdc">
                            <p xml:id="auto_6s0pltl3">
                                Calculate the cyclist's reaction distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_wt46m4ej">
                            <p xml:id="auto_a3coyflx">
                                Determine and explain whether the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_z74hyu2h">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_jnt2bmf1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_87ol2lls">
                               Distance = speed <m>\times</m> time
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_e4h64f88">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ampb6m6j">
                                Reaction distance = <m>5 \times 2 = 10</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3p5r3qsf">
                            <p xml:id="auto_h5z2q1hj">
                                Yes, the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_yggukmkm">
                                The reaction distance of <m>10</m> m is less than the <m>12</m> m available, leaving a safety margin of <m>2</m> m
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qsbejy1x">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m9vej0bo">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_vtazic8z">Provide formula sheets with equations of motion.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5hx9ucr1">Break problems into smaller steps with guided questions.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_s73epnvb">Use visual aids showing reaction and braking phases.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mobqbath">Allow calculators for all calculations.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wd6f6088">Provide worked examples as reference.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yvxublna">Focus on one application area (transportation) before introducing others.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gjiosub4">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cpne78sd">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_6da0yt2r">Introduce more complex scenarios with multiple phases of motion.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ims04p13">Explore non-uniform acceleration problems.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ybyyloq3">Investigate real-world data from crash tests or sports analytics.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_phu42xd7">Design their own safety analysis for a local road.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_itjqf6kj">Research how different road conditions affect braking distance.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mh0pszq8">Calculate energy dissipation during braking.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity: Real-World Safety Analysis Project</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_1cu5iow5">
            Choose a real-world scenario (school zone speed limit analysis, pedestrian crossing safety, sports performance, or elevator design).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3u2dzejv">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_yfx9iool">Collect relevant data (speeds, distances, times, accelerations).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_js2hxidz">Apply linear motion equations to analyse the scenario.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mjcsadgf">Calculate key values (stopping distances, velocities, accelerations).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hzkuabbe">Make safety recommendations based on calculations.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wgdqlw7x">Present findings to the class with visual aids.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
